  "prompt": "How is gender determined genetically?",
  "response": "Gender determination in humans is primarily facilitated by sex chromosomes. Humans typically have 46 chromosomes in each cell, divided into 23 pairs. One of these pairs is responsible for determining sex: the sex chromosomes.\n\n1. **Chromosomal Assignment**: \n   - Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX).\n   - Males typically have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\n\n2. **Fertilization and Genetic Contribution**:\n   - When an egg cell from a female (carrying an X chromosome) is fertilized by a sperm cell from a male, the combination of chromosomes will determine the sex of the offspring.\n   - If the sperm carries an X chromosome and fertilizes the egg, the result will be an XX combination, resulting in a female.\n   - If the sperm carries a Y chromosome and fertilizes the egg, the result will be an XY combination, resulting in a male.\n\n3. **Gene Expression**:\n   - The presence of the Y chromosome is crucial for male development as it carries the SRY gene (Sex-determining Region Y gene), which triggers the development of male characteristics by initiating a cascade of genetic events leading to the formation of testes.\n   - In the absence of the Y chromosome and the SRY gene, the default development pathway leads to the formation of female characteristics.\n\nThough these principles generally hold true, there are exceptions due to variations and disorders (such as Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome, Turner Syndrome, Klinefelter Syndrome, etc.) which may influence gender determination and expression.",
